        "username": "MMachado05",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/community.signalusers.org/mmachado05/{size}/49230_2.png",
        "created_at": "2025-12-12T17:01:56.610Z",
        "cooked": "<p>Currently, when you provide a link to a website that offers an embedded version, the link takes a while to load the embed, as it does it on the client-side, providing some security on the side of the receiver if they don‚Äôt want to make requests to a website they didn‚Äôt know was going to be sent. This is a valid design when security is a high priority.</p>\n<p>However, in practice, it means that most people (in my experience) simply do not send links with embeds. As soon as they‚Äôve pasted the link into the chat, they send it off, leaving the message absent of any suggestion as to what the website content is going to be. Paradoxically, this can <em>further</em> introduce a security risk to the receiver, as now, the only way to get an idea of what‚Äôs on the website is to actually visit it, or to ask the sender what‚Äôs going to be on the website when they click, which introduces friction into the conversation.</p>\n<p>I feel that one good option to improve this would be to, on the first time someone tries to send a message with a link <em>before</em> the embed has loaded, provide a one-time pop-up explaining that they have to wait if they want the embed to send. Something like,</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Link previews are loaded before the message is sent. Do you want to send this message without a link preview?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Of course, this still doesn‚Äôt improve the generally-annoying UX of having to wait before you can send your message just for a link to load.</p>\n<p>So, what if, on that first time a link hasn‚Äôt loaded, an additional option is introduced to essentially ‚Äúthrottle‚Äù messages on the sender side until an embed has loaded? That is, the user would send the message, and it would appear‚Äîvisually‚Äîin the chat log, but it wouldn‚Äôt <em>actually</em> start being sent until <em>after</em> the link has loaded. This eliminates the need for the sender to wait for the embed to load in order to send a message with an embed, without introducing the security risk of rendering the embed in the receiver‚Äôs side, as well.</p>",
        "post_number": 1,
        "post_type": 1,
        "posts_count": 4,
        "updated_at": "2025-12-12T17:01:56.610Z",
