        "id": 281222,
        "name": "",
        "username": "MMachado05",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/community.signalusers.org/mmachado05/{size}/49230_2.png",
        "created_at": "2025-12-16T04:16:06.315Z",
        "cooked": "<p>There‚Äôs another thread linked in that thread where a (then-)Signal developer mentions how this solution was <em>deliberately</em> not implemented, due to the security concerns of rendering a message preview without the recipient‚Äôs consent on their device. However, your direct response to it in that thread (from 4 years ago now, wow!) is also another good solution, I think; prompting the user‚Äîat least the first time‚Äîto wait until the embed loads, at least to relay to them that embeds are loaded <em>before</em> the message is sent.</p>\n<p>That being said, embeds usually load relatively quickly, so I feel like visually sending the message but actually keeping it in a draft until <em>after</em> the embed is loaded would functionally accomplish the same thing, without requiring a pop-up that might bother some users.</p>",
